title: Karina Vetrano: Suspect nabbed in killing of NY jogger, sources say | The Courier-Mail
text:
Karina Vetrano: Man in custody six months after jogger slaying Staff writers, news.com.au 
DETECTIVES are questioning a man over the killing of Queens jogger Karina Vetrano. 
Police sources say a suspected is in custody, the New York Daily News reports. 
Vetrano, 30, was beaten, raped and strangled as she ran through Spring Creek Park in Howard Beach on August 2, 2016. 
Ms Vetrano left her home for a jog around 5pm on August 2, 2016. When she failed to return, family members reported her missing and the search began. 
Her body was found by her father about 14 blocks from her home about 9pm, with the medical examiner’s office later ruling her death a homicide, saying she was strangled. 
Her death sparked a massive manhunt. 
Police recovered her killer’s DNA from Vetrano’s body, but the sample did not match anyone in the New York and national DNA databases of convicted criminals. 
Her parents spoke out last week, trying to renew momentum in their daughter’s case, six months after her body was found, and renewing their calls for police to approve the use of familial DNA to track down her killer. 
Familial DNA testing would allow investigators to find a partial match — possibly a relative of the killer. 
The circumstances behind the suspect’s capture have not been disclosed.
